Explore and visualize your data using ggplot2

Nicolas Legrand (legrand@cyceron.fr)

Load the library, and check the dedicated cheat sheet (Help->Cheatsheets->Data Visualization with ggplot2)

library(ggplot2)

Histogram

Density

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill=Species)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.5)

Boxplot

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length, fill = Species))+
  geom_boxplot(notch = T, 
               lwd = 1.1,
               alpha = 0.5,
               colour = "black")

Dotplot

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length, fill = Species))+
  geom_dotplot(binaxis = "y",
               binwidth = 0.15, 
               stackdir = "center", 
               alpha = 0.5)

Violin

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length, fill = Species))+
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.5, 
              trim = F)

Add Boxplots

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length))+
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.5,
              trim = T,
              aes(fill = Species))+
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.1,
               notch = T)

Dynamit plot

First we need to summarize the data:

library(Rmisc)
sum_data = summarySE(iris,
                     measurevar="Sepal.Length",
                     groupvars = "Species")
knitr::kable(sum_data)
Species N Sepal.Length sd se ci
setosa 50 5.006 0.3524897 0.0498496 0.1001765
versicolor 50 5.936 0.5161711 0.0729976 0.1466942
virginica 50 6.588 0.6358796 0.0899270 0.1807150

Return mean, Standard deviation (sd), Standard error (se) and Confidence interval (ci).

Then plot using the summarized data:

ggplot(sum_data, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length, fill = Species))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", 
           alpha = 0.5, 
           size = 1.5, 
           colour = "black")+
  # Replace "sd" with "se" or "ci" to change error bars
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=Sepal.Length-sd,
                    ymax=Sepal.Length+sd),
                colour = "black",
                width = 0.3, 
                size = 1.8)

Scatter plot

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, col = Species))+
  geom_point(size = 4, 
             alpha = 0.7)+
  # Add slope from linear model and confidence interval
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Scatter plot + density

Adapted from this post.

library(cowplot)
# Define variables
data  = iris
attach(data)
X = Petal.Length
Y = Sepal.Length
Group = Species

# Scatterplot of x and y variables
scatter <- ggplot(data,aes(x= X, y = Y, col = Group)) + 
  geom_point(size = 6, 
             alpha = 0.5) + 
  theme(legend.position=c(2,1),
        legend.justification=c(1,1),
        panel.border= element_rect(colour = "black", size = 1.2, fill = NA),
        plot.margin = unit(c(0.1,0.1,0.1,0.1), "cm")) 

# Marginal density of x - plot on top
plot_top <- ggplot(data, aes(x = X, fill=Group)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.5) + 
  ylab("Density")+
  theme(legend.position = "none",
         axis.title.x = element_blank(),
         axis.text.x = element_blank(),
         axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
         panel.border= element_rect(colour = "black", size = 1.2, fill = NA),
         plot.margin = unit(c(0.1,0.1,0.1,0.1), "cm"))

# Marginal density of y - plot on the right
plot_right <- ggplot(data, aes(x = Y, fill=Group)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.5) + 
  coord_flip() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        panel.border= element_rect(colour = "black", size = 1.2, fill = NA),
        plot.margin = unit(c(0.1,0.1,0.1,0.1), "cm"))

detach(data)

# Arrange the plots together, with appropriate height and width for each row and column
theme_set(theme_gray())

plot_grid(plot_top, NULL, scatter, plot_right, align='hv', rel_heights=c(1,4), rel_widths=c(4,1))

Correlation matrix

Load library

library(corrplot)

Documentation : https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/corrplot/vignettes/corrplot-intro.html

  1. Compute correlation matrix
cor_mat = cor(mtcars)
  • Plot
corrplot(cor_mat, 
         method = "ellipse", # "circle" "square" "number" "shade" "color" "pie"
         type = "upper", # "lower"
         order = "hclust")  # "AOE" "hclust" "alphabet" "FPC"

corrplot(cor_mat, 
         method = "pie", # "circle" "ellipse" "square" "number" "shade" "color" 
         order = "AOE")  # "hclust" "alphabet" "FPC"

corrplot.mixed(cor_mat)

  1. Combine with the significance test
library(Hmisc)
  • Compute matrix of p values
pmat = rcorr(as.matrix(mtcars), 
             type= "pearson")
  • Show p values when > 0.05
corrplot(cor_mat,
         method = "square",
         p.mat = pmat$P,
         sig.level = 0.05,
         insig = "p-value",
         order = "FPC")
